When you think of a small coffee shop in New York, you imagine a busy place where workers are taking in orders by phone whilst getting you coffee as they say good morning to customers coming in.  You picture the guys in the back cooking nonstop on the grill as the orders pour in while the waitresses have that pleasant hurriedness to them - they're not being rude at all they're just busy as can be.  I don't remember what I was doing in the Bronx but I had some time to grab a bite and I opened up maps to find a place.  It looked the part so I went in.  And it was exactly the type of fast-paced coffee shop you would expect.  I sat at the stool because I was alone.  I quickly browsed the menu - not to look through it all but to find what I wanted.  Once I did I stopped browsing it and put my order in.  Soon as I sat coffee greeted me.  When you're in there you step into what NYC was like in the 80's and early 90s.  No nonsense people working hard.  The food was excellent, the service was outstanding and I think I surprised the waitress with my tip.  Whenever I'm in the Bronx I'll be sure to stop by this place.  It was excellent.

Maybe a side of onion rings or fries if you're feeling brave.  The coffee is always hot and fresh. If your're opting for decaf, expect to drink Sanka though it tastes just fine.
